---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import Footer from '../../components/Footer.astro';
import Wordmark from '../../components/Wordmark.astro';
---

<Base
  title="Guide — Pole²"
  description="How to use Pole² and manage it calmly: Android requirements, local install and updates, encrypted backup, safe restore, secure updates and troubleshooting. Everything stays on your device."
>
  <main id="contenuto" class="page">
    <div class="wrap read">
      <p class="eyebrow">Guide</p>
      <h1><Wordmark size="1em" /> — how to use it</h1>
      <p class="lead">
        Pole² keeps the things you care about — and what comes with them — close
        by. Everything stays on your device. Here’s what you can do today.
      </p>

      <h2>Adding a thing</h2>
      <p>Tap Kobe, the turtle at the bottom, and choose how to start:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>From a photo</strong> — take or pick a photo from your gallery, and the new thing starts with its image already in place.</li>
        <li><strong>From a name</strong> — start with a title and add the rest, calmly.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>All you need is a name: nothing is required, you can fill in the rest whenever you like.</p>

      <h2>Photos and gallery</h2>
      <p>
        Every thing can have several photos. The cover is the first image; the
        others stay in the gallery, reorderable, and you can view them full-screen.
      </p>

      <h2>Search and “Where it is”</h2>
      <p>
        From the main screen you can search by name or category, sort, and filter
        with <strong>“Where it is”</strong>: everything, no place, inside a Place,
        or on loan to a person.
      </p>

      <h2>Places</h2>
      <p>
        Places are real containers and can hold one another (Home › Bedroom ›
        Wardrobe). Each thing can sit in a Place or stay without one. A Place’s
        filter includes everything in the places it contains too.
      </p>

      <h2>People: loans, returns and gifts</h2>
      <p>
        You can mark a thing as <strong>lent</strong> to a person, then record its
        <strong>return</strong>. You can also <strong>give</strong> a thing to
        someone for good and — if one day it comes back — record that it’s
        <strong>back among your things</strong>. In the <strong>People</strong>
        section you can see, for each person, what they have on loan, what you’ve
        given them and their history.
      </p>

      <h2>Tidy up this place</h2>
      <p>
        Inside a Place you can start <strong>“Tidy up this place”</strong>: a calm
        walk, one thing at a time, to put what’s there back in order.
      </p>

      <h2>Archive and removed things</h2>
      <p>
        Things that leave everyday use stay readable in the
        <strong>Archive</strong>: those put aside and those removed are kept
        separate. Nothing is deleted for good without a deliberate action from you.
      </p>

      <h2>Encrypted backup and restore</h2>
      <p>
        You can create an <strong>encrypted backup</strong> of your data and
        photos, choosing where to save it. A <strong>restore</strong> replaces the
        current data with the backup’s, keeping a safety copy throughout the
        operation. Only you know the backup password: without it, the backup can’t
        be read.
      </p>

      <h2>Everything on your device</h2>
      <p>
        Pole² works locally: no account, no cloud, no ads. Your data lives on your
        phone, and any sharing is up to you.
      </p>

      <hr class="rule" />

      <p class="eyebrow">Install and maintenance</p>
      <h2 id="requisiti">Requirements</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Android <strong>7.0</strong> or later.</li>
        <li>A <strong>universal Android APK</strong> (a single file, for every compatible device).</li>
        <li>
          Pole² is distributed as a <strong>beta</strong> outside the Google Play
          Store: install it from the <strong>official GitHub Releases</strong> or
          via Pole²’s in-app update.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h2 id="installazione">Install and update</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>
          Download the file <strong>only</strong> from the
          <a href="https://github.com/lcarzaniga/pole2-app/releases" rel="noopener">official Pole² GitHub Release</a>
          or from the <strong>official in-app update</strong>. Don’t download it
          from other sources.
        </li>
        <li>
          When you open the APK, Android may ask you to <strong>allow
          installation</strong> from the app that opened it (your browser or file
          manager).
        </li>
        <li>
          That permission concerns <strong>that source app</strong>, not Pole²:
          you can <strong>turn it off again</strong> after installing.
        </li>
        <li>
          An <strong>in-place</strong> update, signed with the same Pole² key,
          <strong>keeps your data and photos</strong>: there’s no need to
          reinstall from scratch.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Don’t uninstall</strong> Pole² before updating: you’d lose your
          local data. The update installs over the existing version.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h2 id="backup">Backup</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>The backup is <strong>manual and local</strong>: you create it, when you want.</li>
        <li>It contains Pole²’s <strong>database</strong> and the <strong>linked photos</strong>.</li>
        <li><strong>Password protection</strong> is recommended.</li>
        <li>
          A forgotten backup password <strong>can’t be recovered</strong>: without
          it, that backup can’t be read. Keep it safe.
        </li>
        <li>Pole² has <strong>no cloud copies and no account</strong>: no one can reset it for you.</li>
        <li>You choose <strong>where to save the file</strong>.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 id="ripristino">Restore</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>
          A restore <strong>replaces</strong> Pole²’s current contents with the
          backup’s: it <strong>doesn’t merge them</strong>.
        </li>
        <li>
          Pole² <strong>verifies and prepares</strong> the backup before touching
          your active data.
        </li>
        <li>
          It keeps an <strong>emergency safety copy</strong> and, if verification
          fails, <strong>rolls back automatically</strong> to the previous data.
        </li>
        <li>
          To finish, the app <strong>closes and needs to be reopened</strong>.
        </li>
        <li>
          Before restoring, it’s worth creating a <strong>new backup of your
          current data</strong>.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h2 id="aggiornamenti-sicuri">Safe updates</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Some versions may <strong>recommend a backup</strong> before downloading.</li>
        <li>You can still <strong>continue without a backup</strong> or <strong>postpone</strong>.</li>
        <li>Updates <strong>never install by themselves</strong>.</li>
        <li>Pole² <strong>blocks an update while a restore is in progress</strong>.</li>
        <li>Downloaded APKs are <strong>verified with SHA-256</strong> before installing.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 id="problemi">If something goes wrong</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>You’re offline or no update is available:</strong> keep using the
          app and try again later. Nothing gets stuck.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>The install is blocked:</strong> check the
          “<strong>Install unknown apps</strong>” permission for the app that
          opened the APK.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>The restore fails:</strong> Pole² <strong>restores your previous
          local data by itself</strong>.
        </li>
        <li>
          Need help? Write to us from the <a href="/en/supporto">Support</a> page.
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p class="warn">
        For your privacy, <strong>don’t send</strong> backups, databases, photos,
        passwords or sensitive contents of the things you keep in Pole². To help
        you, a description of the problem is enough.
      </p>

      <h2 id="fonti-ufficiali">Official sources</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><a href="https://github.com/lcarzaniga/pole2-app/releases" rel="noopener">Official GitHub Releases</a> — this is where you download the APK.</li>
        <li><a href="/en/privacy">Privacy</a> — what stays on the device and what the site collects.</li>
        <li><a href="/en/supporto">Support</a> — write to us if something isn’t right.</li>
        <li><a href="/en/novita">What’s new</a> — what has changed.</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="muted">
        Pole² isn’t on the Play Store: there’s no official Play Store link. The
        only download channel is the official GitHub Release.
      </p>
    </div>
  </main>
  <Footer />
</Base>

